In its first week of release in Japan, the game topped the weekly chart with sales of 188,562 copies, overtaking [[PlayStation 3]] exclsive ''[[Kamen Rider: Battride War]]'' (2nd) and the PS3 port of ''[[Resident Evil: Revelations]]''.<ref name= "FirstWeekSale">{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/05/shin_megami_tensei_iv_storms_to_number_one_in_japanese_charts|title=Shin Megami Tensei IV Storms to Number One in Japanese Charts|author=Whitehead, Thomas|publisher=Nintendo Life|date=29 May 2013|accessdate=20 October 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20131023002547/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/05/shin_megami_tensei_iv_storms_to_number_one_in_japanese_charts|archivedate=23 October 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> By the end of 2013, the game had sold 251,334 copies in Japan, and was the country's 30th best-selling video game of the year.<ref name= "LRsales2013">{{cite web|url=http://geimin.net/da/db/2013_ne_fa/index.php | language=Japanese| title=GEIMIN.NET<U+FF0F>2013<U+5E74><U+30C6><U+30EC><U+30D3><U+30B2><U+30FC><U+30E0><U+30BD><U+30D5><U+30C8><U+58F2><U+308A><U+4E0A><U+3052><U+30E9><U+30F3><U+30AD><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+FF08><U+30D5><U+30A1><U+30DF><U+901A><U+7248><U+FF09>|accessdate=20 October 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140424073230/http://geimin.net/da/db/2013_ne_fa/index.php|archivedate=24 April 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> By January 2014, the game had sold 90,000 copies in the United States since its release in July.<ref name= "-">{{cite web|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/december-2013-npd-lifetime-sales-for-wii-u-and-3ds-titles/|title=December 2013 NPD: lifetime sales for Wii U and 3DS titles|author=Brian|publisher=Nintendo Everything|date=17 January 2014|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>

The title has received critical acclaim in both Japan and the west. Aggregate sites [[GameRankings]] and [[Metacritic]] gave it rankings of 83.93% and 83/100 based on 31 and 32 critic reviews respectively.<ref name="GameRank"/><ref name="MetaCritic"/> The battle system received universal praise, with ''[[Famitsu]]'', [[IGN]], [[GameSpot]], [[Eurogamer]], [[Joystiq]], [[Destructoid]], [[Game Informer]] and ''Nintendo World Report'': all cited the battle system as highly enjoyable despite difficulty spikes and praised the game making allowances for newcomers.<ref name="GSpot"/><ref name= "Eurogamer"/><ref name="IGN"/><ref name= "GameInform"/><ref name="Famitsu"/><ref name="Joystiq"/><ref name= "Destructoid"/><ref name= "NinWorldRep">{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/34877/shin-megami-tensei-iv-nintendo-3ds|title=Shin Megami Tensei IV|author=Baker, Justin|publisher=Nintendo World Report|date=10 July 2013|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> The negotiation and fusions systems were also praised, with several reviewers noting it as both entertaining and an improvement on previous versions.<ref name= "Eurogamer"/><ref name="IGN"/><ref name= "GameInform"/><ref name= "Destructoid"/><ref name= "NinWorldRep"/> A gameplay aspects that received criticism was navigation via the over world map, which was called either difficult to follow or poorly designed.<ref name="IGN"/><ref name= "Destructoid"/><ref name="GSpot"/><ref name= "GameInform"/>

The story and characters had a mixed reception: while Destructoid and ''Nintendo World Report'' were generally positive,<ref name= "Destructoid"/><ref name= "NinWorldRep"/> other reviews such as Eurogamer and Game Informer felt that the characters were only there to represent the player's moral pathways.<ref name= "Eurogamer"/><ref name= "GameInform"/> IGN, Joystiq, and GameSpot were fairly negative about them, calling them either irritating or forgettable.<ref name="GSpot"/><ref name="IGN"/><ref name="Joystiq"/> The graphics, while praised by some reviewers, were sometimes seen as either bland or of low-quality.<ref name= "Eurogamer"/><ref name="IGN"/><ref name= "GameInform"/><ref name= "Destructoid"/>
